segments.text: And I'm in the office here in Bryan of Mr. A.W.
Davis, Sr. And we want to talk to him about his recollections of student life.
OK. A.W.
Davis, Jr. And now I'm going to stop and see if the machine's working.
OK. First question.
Why did you attend A&M in the first place?
What led you here?
What caused you to come to this place?
My response would be, doctor, that during high school years, I really had intended to matriculate at Southern Methodist.
Being a Methodist by tradition, that sounded good to me.
And I suppose I would have done that save and except I had a first cousin who lived in Sherman.

who was in the class of 44 and he visited me one day probably in my junior or senior year in high school probably senior and he said to me that he was a Baptist and he said Southern Methodist was not the place for you and you need to be at Texas A&M.
I'm not sure I'd ever heard of Texas A&M before but
I'd have to lay it on my cousin whose name is LT Davis.

He turned out to be a long practicing veterinarian and as I said was in the class of 44 and now resides in Denison and I reminded him of that conversation within the past short months but that's the only reason I can assign.
Did you come to visit before you came down to enroll?
I came
hitchhike down here in the spring.
Beautiful weather, I recall, of 1941.
There were a good handful of Wichita Falls boys at Texas A&M.
Lord, there was Jimmy Handy, Jimmy Keel,
A good half dozen here.
And I paid them a visit.
They were quartered mostly over in what we came to call the new area.
And I did see them.
And I suppose had the money to spend the night.
And I don't know why I didn't stay in the dormitory with them.
Probably could have.
But I spent the night in a motel in the block immediately south of Brass County Courthouse as it was then and now.
So I did visit here in the spring of 1941.
What was your impression?
Well, I was age 16.
I thought it was a very peaceful place.
I did not see very much of the Corps activities.
Might have seen them march into the mess hall.
I can't recall that, but I certainly had to notice those uniforms.
And of course,
It was the time to be thinking about a uniform, and I'm not sure I was thinking about anything, but it was the time, whether I was thinking or not, to see what kind of uniform you'd go wear.
This was 1941.
Did anybody promise you anything if you came here?
No.
Nobody gave you a sales pitch?
No.
I remember looking at the catalog.
the library in the high school in Wichita Falls had a collection of catalogs and I looked at several of them and I can remember looking at one in regard to A&M College.
Seemed to me the matriculation fee was $25.
I can't believe that's correct but that's my memory.
I read a little bit about it.
I told some people around
The high school that I was going to come to Texas A&M, I distinctly remember one fellow and one fellow only told me that I could come and stay in Texas A&M.
Everybody else said I could not do that.
This fellow, there were two pressing brothers that taught school.
One was an assistant principal, and I believe that was A.K.
Preston.
My name was Fred in those days, and he said, Oh, Fred, you can do that.
And I said, Mr. Preston, I'm getting ready to graduate in the third quarter of my class.
He said, Yes, but you can do it.
No one else, except my father and mother, they knew I could do anything, but they were highly prejudiced.
Everybody else said I could not last at Texas A&M.
It had a good reputation for people coming and some not staying.
Alright, describe the campus physically when you arrived.
What buildings were where?
What did it look like?
That's not real difficult to do.
I imagine what we now know as Texas Avenue was probably a two-lane strip of concrete leading from
Brian, College Station 2, Houston.
I was, I can reflect now that the East Gate was every bit as pretty then to me as it is now.
At the East Gate was the Blue Top Motel.
Probably called Tourist Court then, I'm not sure, but that's kind of what it was.
Blue Top
motel, I'd call it, a number of little individual units.

There was a restaurant at the East Gate in a building that I've since come to know was owned by George Ciceres, one of the outstanding members of a clan of Greek businessmen and women in Bryan and College.
That was a restaurant.
The building still stands and is still on this date in the Ciceres family.
And Dr. Walton's old office, TT, was there.

The semi-circular entrance to College Hills Estate, I remember being there and having some buildings, but the entrance to what I called the white building, in other words, the old standby administration building, was just as pretty then as it is now.
I also like the petroleum engineering building.

It had a beautiful, it's called a cupola, a structure on top of the functional building itself and I loved on let's say Tuesday and Thursday or it was Monday, Wednesday, and Friday I had a class in that building.
And I'd do my best to go early and maybe even stay a little late because it was a grassy knoll there and I could look out and see the cars.
Every now and then there'd be a car going down Highway 6 towards Navasota.
And I'd think how nice it would be to be in one of those automobiles and get to go somewhere.
Kyle Field, of course, was
as it had been probably since the middle 30s.
I can't be certain, but there were no second or third decks and so on.
Beware Fieldhouse, of course, was there.
An old building that I went to school in had a course in there.
It was called Pfeiffer Hall.
It had to be one of the oldest on the campus.
It's now gone.
Ross Hall.
and Austin Hall were there.
Ross Hall was the office of the commandant.
And where were they located?
Well, if one went out the west door of the academic building and looked towards the southern Pacific tracks, one was to the right and one was to the left in the same block.
Gathright Hall was missing.
Gathright was said to be, and I can't be accurate about this, but was said to be the oldest building on the campus.
It was a common practice of the sophomores to say to a freshman, I want you to locate Gathright Hall.
As a matter of fact, Gathright Hall was gone.
There was a little marker on the former location of Gathright, which was adjacent to what was then called, and the building still stands, the student exchange.
Of course, had a bugle stand out in front of Sabisa, and that meant something.
Over in the new area, where the 12 cell blocks are, at the northwest corner was a frame building, and in that building was what I'd call, and was called in those days, it was George's Confectionary.
George McCullough owned that place.
And he sat on a high stool and took nickels in.
Occasionally dying.
Post office was in the other end and there was a cleaner there.
And you'd get hamburgers and fountain drinks there and so on.
George McCullough later became a very good client of mine as his family has been for years and years.
The dormitories opposite what was called Campus Theater at the North Gate, we call that the New New Area.
There were four or five dormitories built in the spring or summer, spring, I suppose, in 1942.
Other than that, the most recent dormitories on the campus has been the New Area, which is 12 dormitories.
They were there in 1941.
Just your impression of the academic building.
Oh, I was in there a bunch.
And it did appear to me that it was larger than Wichita Falls Senior High School, I'll say that.
I had a lot of classes there.
And it was enormous, and it was huge to me.
And I'm glad it's still there.
How were fish treated during your freshman year?
Describe being a fish in 1941.
That's easy.
That is a part of my indelible memory.

When I came here in September of 1941, I had been late registering, and I could not live with a military unit to which I had been assigned, which was 3rd Headquarters Battery on a field artillery, number four in the new area.
I lived about 10 days in Bazell Hall, which was a part of the Coastal Artillery Regiment.
And I soon asked somebody where Bazell Hall was, and I was approaching the building, and the sophomore fellow said to me, pick that footlocker up and follow me.
And we went to the fourth floor of Bazell Hall.
That was my orientation and from then on it went down.
Freshman life at Texas A&M is hard to describe in a way that might be believed because people would be incredulous truly about what went on.
Short of the incarceration of the Vietnam prisoners of war, it had to be the worst
say, four to five months of existence has anybody ever lived in the free world.
Do you want to hear more?
A freshman wore a white strap on the cuff of their left sleeve, and that stayed on there the entire freshman year, and that entitled you to walk in the streets.
did not entitle you to sit in any park bench on the Indian campus unless you were with a visitor.
It entitled you to attend bleep meetings.
Bleep meetings were orientation sessions conducted by sophomores in the halls of the dormitories whereupon you were instructed how to attend to your business.
And those were important instructions in a sense.
And in another sense, even if you followed them, it got you nowhere.
You were in a heck of a mess until they eased up, say, in March of our freshman year.
Every now and then, a freshman would commit an error of commission or omission of sufficient magnitude to even get
the juniors and seniors involved.
And when that happened, it was truly the end of the world.
As far as I know, every unit on the campus, and certainly the one I was in, believed in liberal applications of the board.
That meant a baseball bat trimmed to a smooth surface in the middle of the bat.
And it, at least that's what it resembled.
And these boards were prevalent, most of them in the hands of softball.
And they would tell you to grab a pooch.
That meant that you would tighten the muscles in your rumpus and turn your rumpus to them.
And they would administer three severe
legs to your posterior anatomy and it hurt.
But that was the easiest part.
The toughest part of it was the push-ups, holding the wall up, and all the other physical and mental things that went with it.
It was severe.
About how often did that occur?
You mean the bleed meeting?
Or at least once or twice a week.
the application, were the number of bleed meetings comparatively similar unit to unit?
I would think so.
Of course, I was never in a unit.
Oh, with minor exception except my own because you were obligated to go to class and you were obligated to do that.
And you were obligated to come back to your room.
You were
allowed, of course, to go to the post office.
That was accomplished to and from the classroom.
You could go to some athletic events.
That is to say, you certainly could go to a football game, but you couldn't go to all basketball games because there were certain study requirements.
You had to be in your room with the door closed and that kind of thing.
But you couldn't go up to the north gate unless a sophomore or a classmate was sending you
Were freshman roommates special?
Fish, old lady, did you have a special friend who?
I roomed with a boy named Angus Dixon, who was a good student and a nice fellow from Terrell, Texas.
I later roomed with Dickie Haas, my old partner from Corpus Christi, now deceased.
Pete Slaughter came along somewhere.
Boy, this was after the war.
that I knew Pete best, a class of 44 boy from Houston.
Oh, yes, you freshmen lived with freshmen, sophomores lived with sophomores, and so on.
You were a room orderly to somebody, some upperclassmen.
And you attended to making their beds and did not shine shoes.
You did not do that.
But you did make those beds, and you did

police the room and as a matter of fact my clothes still hang in my closet with the coat hangers pointing all in one direction in a certain space from each other and it's just as orderly as it was in 1941 because they taught me very quickly.
What about life in the in the dining hall?
Describe dining in Duncan Hall I guess it was in your case.
Everybody marched to the mess hall three times a day.
There probably was some compulsion to that.
Very few meals were missed, and there's more than one reason, as I recall.
One of them was the food was excellent.
The main food service fellow on the campus at that time was named Mr. Hotar.
And he and his folks did a superior job.
I remember it being excellent food.
There was noise in the mess hall.
It was family service.
You, of course, had some strict things to observe.
You weren't going to serve yourself before every upperclassman was served.
But I don't recall a great deal of disturbance in the mess hall.
They did allow you to eat.
I ate well.
Were there any names for various food items?
Oh, yeah.
I can't recall.
Bonac was any kind of meat.
like me saw was saying any kind of dessert was cush.
It seems to me freshmen did not eat cushion until after Thanksgiving.
That was supposed to help you beat Texas in football.
Let me think.
I think mustard was baby.
I can't remember.
I'm having difficulty with that.
But they are pretty well named.
I think Cal
Yes, and bull wasn't, I think, any kind of bread.
They all had names.
Let's see, did you all ever attempt any pranks at mealtime?
Any tricks, games?
I devoted most of my subversive activity to trying to get Cush.
I don't recall any organized activity in the mess hall.
As a matter of fact, you could do what you wanted to, but you paid an enormous price.
The freshman life at Texas A&M has been helpful to me because since then, I have been involved in numerous jams of all kinds.
It seems like I can get in trouble and get my plow hung without any difficulty at all.
And in the darkest moments, I will
I have always been able to reflect this is not as bad as a fish year at A&M.
It's given me a standard and I've never excelled at it.
Was your outfit special to you as you look back in shaping you, forming you?
There were some great and good fellas in third and head quarterback at the field artillery regiment.
It only lasted and was in existence about
four, perhaps five years, something had happened before I arrived that caused Third Headquarters Battery to be organized.
And it, one of its, maybe its first commander was Billy Joel.
Oh, mercy and embarrassment, Billy Joel.
He taught an executive development course in the business college at A&M.
For years and years.
Billy Joe McAdams.
Billy Joe Adams.
Good guy.
He had been the battery commander.
He was gone when I arrived.
Jack Taylor, a fellow from Irene, who was a good soldier, if there ever was one, was the battery commander.
And after that was a fellow named Tudor Ball from Uvalde.
And after that, a fellow named Bob Parker, who lived then at Robie, now lives in Paris, Texas.
Yeah, it was a great outfit.
We had good soldiers.
Except for me.
I had a difficult time.
Take me, describe, if you will, a typical class day.
When did it start?
What happened when?
When did it end?
Well, in those days, by golly, it was not unusual.
As a matter of fact, I'd say it was unusual that a student took 18 hours.
That included a certain amount of military service.
I didn't pass any of them, but I took them.
And you certainly had to be up early in the morning.
The hour escapes me, but you had to have time to get your room in shape and get your Lord and Master's room in shape.
Did you wake up on your own?
What awakened you?

No, there was a bugle that was blown down in front of Duncan Hall and over the people in the other area, the older part of the campus at Bugle Stand, right by the old Calvary dormitories down from the space of it.
You had to have that done by breakfast time, and then you marched to breakfast.
You returned, probably brushed your teeth, got out in the free world going to class if you had an 8 o'clock class.
classes then were Monday through Friday and Saturday morning.
And sometime that week in the afternoon you would have a drill where the unit would participate in some kind of military exercise.
Post-order drill or service of the peace or whatever it might have been.
Where and how long would that occur?
Where did you all drill?
Close order drill would likely be conducted right in the dormitory area.
But by the time I was a sophomore, perhaps even four, we would march down to the field artillery stables.
My battery was a horse-drawn unit.
And the cavalry and the field artillery had many horses.
on what's now called the west campus.
The staples were right west of the railroad tracks that now exist.
And you would saddle those horses, put them on in the pieces, to pull the pieces.
And you might go to the Brazzers spot.
Other times, you'd run problems, military exercises for field artillery.
in what's now called Hensel Park.
Many times we've done that.
And you learn how to operate a feel-like inner battery.
If you had an unscheduled afternoon, what'd you do?
I don't know that this speaks to the afternoon, but it certainly would speak to the early evening.
Inner murals was a big part
Texas A&M at the time had all kinds of intramural activities, and I don't know that you had to participate in it, but you were encouraged to do so.
And they began in the late afternoon and so on before dinner that evening, softball, football, everything, boxing, whatever might have been the time to do.
Was it easy, though, for a freshman to go over and sack out in the afternoon in his room?
Oh, you didn't do that.
Freshmen change places.
That is to say, I had freshmen from the infantry regiment come to my room because my sophomores were not bothered.
So I had to go over to their place and seek a little refuge.
You did that occasionally.
It wasn't altogether customary, but you could do that on occasion.
All right, then now we're getting ready for supper.
Tell me the routine of getting ready and whatever happened before supper.
I thought that was a great time.
You knew what time that event was going to go down.
And you assembled in the battery area, the battery walk, let's say, that led directly to Duncan.
And Captain Jack Taylor would take his position.
field artillery regiment on the west and the infantry regiment on the east.
And dormitory, I guess, dormitory on the east closest to Duncan Hall would be 11.
I believe that's correct.
The band was there in those days.
12 was occupied by the scholarship athletes.
At a later time they were
moved into the units.
But at that time, early freshman days, they lived in 12.
Anyway, it was a marvelous time.
It rained once in a while, but when it wasn't, I kind of liked that.
It was a little retreat.
I kind of liked the sound of the vehicle, and you could hear these commanders giving the command down the line.
I kind of liked that a little bit.
And for that few brief moments, sophomores weren't fooling with you.
Okay, then you went in and ate.
Then after supper, what happened?
You went to your room shortly.
Not much hiatus there at all.
And did what?
You were supposed to stay.
I'm sure.
I said, my desk is asleep.
But you were supposed to stay.
How long?
I can't recall.
I would say that lights out were probably, I'm guessing, maybe 9.30, 10 perhaps.
I don't know.
How did you dress?
What did you wear to class and the dining hall?
We wore a uniform.
They'd tell you what the uniform of the day was, that is to say,
You knew, but you didn't know about jackets or raincoats or whatever that announced that.
First Sergeant, I recall, would announce that.
And you wore uniforms all the time.
Period.
What kind of head?
Oh, mercy.
What was the finest headgear that there's ever been?
A campaign hat.
Except when you had on the old blue lapel.
Class A ROTC uniform for a parade or something such as that, and then you wore a garrison cap.
But the campaign hats were marvelous.
They really were.
What about jokes, pranks, good bull from any of your years, either that you knew about or perhaps participated in or observed?
Can you share any?
Oh, they had a lot of things going.
It's hard for me to recall.
Probably the worst thing that happened, me and three or four others in my unit, was during the fall, sometime, we were placed in the doghouse.
And the doghouse meant strictly, no, you were out of your room for one purpose, and that was to go to class.
Other than that, you were in your room at all times.
And we had to...
very much like the Vietnam fellow, we had to find a way to communicate from the second floor to the third floor and that kind of thing.

And there was always this old deal of taking a cow into somebody's, into somebody's dormitory room, you understand, trying to get them upstairs and perhaps spend the weekend in there and come back and find the mess.
But let me tell you, there wasn't
It took a brave freshman to do very much.
But even as an upperclassman, did anybody's footlocker ever get missing?
The biggest prank-type deal that I can recall, one that I abhorred, was a drowning out whereby a bucket of water would be tossed into somebody's room.
It seemed like they wanted to pick on mine
And that meant that I had to clean it up.
I deplored that activity, but drowning out was a big deal.
How did life change for a sophomore?
It got worse for me.
Everybody else had it better, but I got worse.
My sophomore year, we moved from number four
